# I Love Markdown
Key Points 
Convert Markdown to PDF functionality
Registration page removed (only login available)
Initial Analysis
The challenge started with only a login page, without any known credentials. This hinted at the possibility of SQL Injection (SQLi) being the way forward.

At first, I tried common payloads such as:
'
'-- -
'or 1=1--
But the application did not throw SQL errors. Instead, it only showed “Invalid credentials”. This suggested that the back-end was handling or suppressing SQL errors.
Exploiting SQLi
Trying with different payloads only UNION attack works. So the payloads looks like:
' Union select null,group_concat(username || ' : ' || password) from users-- 
This web application usages SQLite, so to concate ||  operator is used. Moving forward it gives us a username and password that allowed authentication into the web application.

Post-Login Functionality
After logging in, the application provided a feature to convert Markdown to PDF.
To test this, I generated a sample PDF. Upon inspecting its metadata, I noticed that the conversion tool used was wkhtmltopdf.


Identifying Vulnerability
The version of wkhtmltopdf in use was known to be vulnerable to Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF). Reference: https://www.exploit-db.com/exploits/51039. Additionally, examining the HTML source revealed commented hints suggesting SSRF. The application was running with gunicorn, which by default listens on port 8000.

Exploitation
Using the SSRF vulnerability in wkhtmltopdf, I crafted a payload to request an internal resource:
<iframe src="http://localhost:8000/hidden.html" width="800" height="200" > </iframe>

This successfully allowed me to retrieve the flag.
By combining SQL Injection with SSRF in wkhtmltopdf, the flag was successfully retrieved. Thanks for reading my writeup, and good luck on your own hacking journey